│ simplifies `select i1 %cmp2, i1 %cmp1, i1 false` to `%cmp1`. This transformation is        │
│ equivalent to simplifying `C && X` to `X`, which is only valid if `X` implies `C`.         │
│                                                                                            │
│ In the provided reproducer:                                                                │
│ - `C` is `%cmp2 = icmp ne i8 %x, 0`                                                        │
│ - `X` is `%cmp1 = icmp samesign eq i8 %x, -1`                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The implication `(icmp samesign eq i8 %x, -1)` => `(icmp ne i8 %x, 0)` is not always true. │
│ Specifically, when `%x` is 0:                                                              │
│ - `%cmp1` becomes `poison` because `samesign` requires operands to have the same sign (0   │
│ is non-negative, -1 is negative).                                                          │
│ - `%cmp2` is `false`.                                                                      │
│ - The original `select` evaluates to `false`.                                              │
│ - The simplified expression evaluates to `poison`.                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ The transformation is therefore incorrect as it introduces `poison` where a well-defined   │
│ value existed. The core of the issue is that the `isImpliedCondition` utility in           │
│ `ValueTracking.cpp` does not correctly handle the `poison`-generating behavior of the      │
│ `samesign` `icmp` flag.                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Proposed Fix                                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to make `isImpliedCondition` more conservative. When it encounters an `icmp`    │
│ instruction with the `samesign` flag, it should not attempt to prove any implication and   │
│ should instead return `std::nullopt`. This will prevent the incorrect optimization from    │
│ occurring.                                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will add a check for `RHSCmp->hasSameSign()` within the `isImpliedCondition` function in │
│ `llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp`.                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Implementation                                                                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now use the `edit` tool to apply the fix.                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ <tool_call>                                                                                │
│ {                                                                                          │
│   "name": "edit",                                                                          │
│   "args": {                                                                                │
│     "file": "llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp",                                         │
│     "old": "  if (const ICmpInst *RHSCmp = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(RHS)) {\n    if (auto        │
│ Implied = isImpliedCondition(\n            LHS, RHSCmp->getCmpPredicate(),                 │
│ RHSCmp->getOperand(0),\n            RHSCmp->getOperand(1), DL, LHSIsTrue, Depth))\n        │
│ return InvertRHS ? !*Implied : *Implied;\n    return std::nullopt;\n  }",                  │
│     "new": "  if (const ICmpInst *RHSCmp = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(RHS)) {\n    // If the       │
│ checked comparison can be poison, we can't assume anything.\n    if                        │
│ (RHSCmp->hasSameSign())\n      return std::nullopt;\n\n    if (auto Implied =              │
│ isImpliedCondition(\n            LHS, RHSCmp->getCmpPredicate(), RHSCmp->getOperand(0),\n  │
│ RHSCmp->getOperand(1), DL, LHSIsTrue, Depth))\n      return InvertRHS ? !*Implied :        │
│ *Implied;\n    return std::nullopt;\n  }"                                                  │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ }                                                                                          │
